<DOCNO> AP880608-0012 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency says it 
will be safe to test a banned termitekiller in houses and other 
occupied dwellings even though an environmental groups calls it 
using humans as guinea pigs 
we dont see it as human testing says james roelofs epas 
review manager for chlordane a widely used chemical that epa says 
could pose longterm health risks including cancer 
roelofs made the statement tuesday after a watchdog group 
criticized an epaapproved plan calling for at least 150 residences 
around the nation to be treated with the chemical 
this amounts to epasanctioned human testing of a pesticide 
said jay feldman national coordinator of the national coalition 
against the misuse of pesticides 
under the plan chlordane would be applied at unidentified test 
sites at no cost to homeowners air inside the homes would be 
monitored for two years to detect any levels of chlordane 
chlordane was used for 40 years to termiteproof an estimated 30 
million dwellings but sale of chlordane for residential 
applications was halted last august under an agreement between epa 
and velsicol chemical corp the illinoisbased manufacturer of the 
pesticide 
epa said detectable levels of chlordane inside houses raised 
concerns that longterm exposure to low levels of chlordane could 
pose health risks including an increased risk of developing 
cancer 
the agreement halted chlordane sales by velsicol until the 
company could conduct further testing and show that no home 
involved in the new study had detectable levels of chlordane in its 
indoor air 
roelofs said the new tests will involve application methods that 
are different from the traditional ways chlordane was applied 
the chemical will be placed in the ground around a house or 
under a concrete slab foundation rather than being injected into 
the concrete itself according to roelofs 
there may be an element of risk to the inhabitants but we 
have reason to believe its low roelofs said by eliminating 
pressure injections and any injection inside the house its 
possible there wont be any detectable levels its a reasonable 
expectation 
roelofs said epa and velsicol wont know whether the new 
application methods produce indoor levels of chlordane until 
theres been some testing 
he said the airmonitoring tests could be conducted at 
unoccupied dwellings but that this was not proposed by either epa 
or velsicol 
we think its within reason that if you dont put the material 
in the house it wont get into the house roelofs said 
theyre going to apply it in a way thats least likely to lead to 
exposure 
donna jennings velsicols public affairs manager said the 
company did not consider using unoccupied dwellings because 
theres no evidence to say chlordane is a human health hazard 
she said velsicol reached the agreement with epa rather than 
face the drawnout negative publicity that could accompany 
fighting a formal epa regulatory move against chlordane 
roelofs said the agency acted against chlordane because we 
were being very conservative about the results of earlier tests 
showing the chemical leached into indoor air 
jennings said the new testing wont begin until the company and 
epa settle the issue of whether the names of the participating 
homeowners will be kept secret 
we dont want them harassed she said 
feldman says his organization wants the test locations made 
public so that we can notify potential participants of the 
hazards people participating in what amounts to a human 
testing experiment will receive no neutral objective information 
he said the information epa wants velsicol to give participants 
is weak and when taken together with the other material velsicol 
plans to circulate will leave potential participants in their 
study with a distorted view of the risks that they face 
</TEXT>
