<TEXT>
the leftist sandinista government and 
usbacked rebels moved closer to a settlement as they began 
another round of peace talks both sides reported progress on the 
key issue of democratic reforms 
negotiators who meet again today discussed on tuesday a 
government proposal that a sandinista official said accedes to 
nearly all contra rebel demands for ending the ruling partys 
political monopoly 
before they lay down their arms and end six years of fighting 
the rebels want guaranteed freedom of the press an end to 
sandinista control of the army and government the right to strike 
and judicial and electoral reforms 
we have made substantial advances information minister 
manuel espinoza said after tuesdays session in managua that opened 
the fourth round of negotiations since the foes signed a preliminary 
peace accord on march 23 
bosco mamatoros spokesman for the rebels said there were 
advances in the discussion on themes of a substantial character 
but added that political reform remains the biggest problem in the 
discussions 
a government representative who spoke on condition of anonymity 
said earlier that the sandinistas had agreed to nearly all rebel 
demands for political reform 
the sandinista proposal was also said to offer the contras a role 
in talks begun late last year between the government and domestic 
opposition parties 
an american negotiator for the government said tuesday that the 
two main obstacles to a definitive settlement were the fine print of 
disarmament and amnesty for jailed contras 
paul reichler a washingtonbased attorney said the sandinistas 
want full disarmament and reintegration of the contras into civilian 
life by the end of september he said the rebels had proposed laying 
down their weapons by the end of january 
reichler said the rebel proposal was linked to the us 
presidential elections in november and january inauguration of a new 
president to preserve a military option 
he called it one last roll of the dice on a george bush 
victory the vice president is the likely republican nominee 
but the sandinista proposal also may be linked to the us 
elections 
a ceasefire in hand by november would favor the democrats a 
majority of whom have opposed continued us military assistance for 
the rebels it also would represent an embarrassment for the 
republican administration 
the democratic majority in congress rejected president reagans 
last request for additional military aid to the rebels which ended 
feb 26 congress last approved a military aid package for the 
contras in june 1986 that totalled 100 million 
reichler said the contras also wanted to change the amnesty plan 
agreed to by both sides in march that plan calls on the government 
to release half of jailed rebels after contra combatants move into 
truce zones and the remainder at a still undetermined date 
he said the contras are calling for the release of all prisoners 
five days after the rebels move into the truce areas 
the talks are taking place amid a temporary truce enacted march 
21 the rebels have extended the truce until thursday and the 
government has declared a unilateral ceasefire until the end of 
june 
each side accuses the other of violations 
heavy fighting was reported tuesday near juigalpa capital of 
central chontales state a sandinista soldier who asked not to be 
identified told the associated press the fighting involved at least 
70 contras and 50 army troops 
two contras were captured and an undetermined number of 
government troops were wounded and taken by helicopter to a hospital 
in juigalpa he said 
