<TEXT>
independent religious activists are demanding that 
the russian orthodox church retract its past praise of josef v 
stalin and embrace the soviet unions new spirit of reforms 
they are urging the church to follow the lead of other soviet 
organizations that are reevaluating and condemning stalins 
dictatorship 
on tuesday nearly 100 religious dissidents from around the 
soviet union packed a moscow apartment for an unofficial threeday 
seminar on religious problems in the soviet union 
father gleb yakunin told reporters the church is at a crossroads 
its the responsibility of the church to announce which side 
it is on the side of perestroika or the side of stalinism he 
said a person cannot be renewed in his personal life unless he 
repents this is true of the church 
perestroika or restructuring is what mikhail s gorbachev 
calls his ambitious program of social and economic reforms 
church activists released copies of an appeal they sent to 
patriarch pimen the russian orthodox church leader asking that 
the church council condemn a 1949 letter it sent to stalin for his 
70th birthday basically canonizing the dictator 
the church told stalin it was forever grateful to you for your 
attentiveness to its needs 
so far the church has kept silent on stalin while many other 
soviets including gorbachev have sharply criticized the 
dictators purges which killed or exiled millions of people 
after stalin took power a law was passed in 1929 sharply 
restricting church activities the church faced its severest 
repression in the 1930s when cathedrals were demolished and other 
church property seized by the state 
yakunin and other religious activists met with reporters on the 
second day of the russian orthodox church local council in zagorsk 
northeast of moscow 
the council is at the center of celebrations of christianitys 
arrival 1000 years ago in russia 
yakunin was barred from performing religious rites from 1966 
until last year because of his criticism of church officials he 
also is a former political prisoner in august the church gave him 
a small parish near moscow 
the dissidents criticized the selection of delegates for the 
church council in zagorsk and the amount of money being spent on 
the millennium celebration 
ceremonies scheduled at moscows bolshoi theater threaten to 
turn the event in a pompous theatrical action yakunin said 
each day of the weeklong celebration costs about 16 million 
he said 
