<TEXT>
jesse jackson the unvanquished loser is 
promising a postprimary workout for michael dukakis that could put 
the democratic nominee in prime condition for his general election 
bout with george bush 
but dukakis cant afford a messy convention or other major 
missteps as the next six weeks test his mettle as a negotiator and a 
leader 
dukakis has the 1988 democratic presidential nomination firmly in 
hand after four big victories on tuesdays final round of 1988 
primaries jackson cant shake dukakiss grip on the nominating 
majority at the atlanta convention 
but he has plenty of time to pressure dukakis before and during 
the democratic national convention in atlanta in july 
the intensely determined massachusetts governor expects some 
fireworks from the fiery preacher indeed he seems almost to be 
welcoming them 
we may have a contest or two we may have a floor fight or 
two dukakis said in los angeles on tuesday there may be some 
issues that go to the floor i dont see any great divisions within 
our party 
jackson promised to take the south african issue to the 
convention floor if the party platform does not measure up to his 
standard of denouncing of that apartheid regime as terrorist 
dukakis almost invited the fight tuesday night by saying that 
label is meaningless 
his attitude toward possible floor fights at the convention is a 
healthy one for two reasons 
one floor fights are not necessarily bad 
a little drama and conflict makes good television in what could 
otherwise be a very dull four days in july in atlanta but 
outofcontrol ideological spats have marred past democratic 
conventions making many party professionals anxious to avoid them 
second the more dukakis refuses to give into pressure from the 
left wing of the democratic party on the issues the better he is 
positioned to ward off attacks from republican george bush 
in a similar way jackson stepped up the pressure on the vice 
presidential spot tuesday even as the massachusetts governor was 
crushing him in primaries in california montana new jersey and new 
mexico 
jackson declared flatly he deserves consideration for the 
nomination a point dukakis has agreed with even though he hasnt 
made up his mind about an offer 
ive not yet made that decision but i have certainly earned 
consideration jackson said after the votes were tallied tuesday 
and the civil rights leader added a new twist to his demands 
that dukakis balance his ticket ideologically with a liberal 
mr dukakis said in many ways he is more conservative than 
george bush jackson said he has the right to express his point 
of viewso he is a fiscal conservative 
it means the ticket must be balanced therefore with a 
progressive 
such a characterization cannot help but please the liberal 
massachusetts governor if only privately 
when the leading proponent of the democratic partys left wing 
calls you a conservative it is a useful antidote to the attacks 
from bush 
the republican nomineetobe has been trying mightily in the past 
two months to paint dukakis as a farout liberal as a george 
mcgovern dove on defense and a walter mondale taxraiser in budget 
matters 
such attacks are designed to frame the general election race in a 
straightforward liberalconservative terms a structure dukakis 
would like to forget about as he talks of change and efficient 
management of government without reference to ideology 
there are substantial pitfalls for dukakis in this shortterm 
contest of wills with jackson 
he must of course avoid alienating jackson or his constituents 
as the battles continue through atlanta he needs the enthusiastic 
support of jacksons backers and a big turnout from them on nov 8 
if he is beat bush 
any refusal to talk to jackson to listen at length to his 
concerns would fly in the face of his demand that his supporters 
must be heard respectfully at every level in the party 
and any direct attacks on jackson by dukakis would cause problems 
in the fall 
unlike some other democratic hopefuls dukakis also avoided much 
criticism of jackson something the civil rights leader noted in 
praising dukakis for running a campaign free of demagoguery and 
attacks 
but dukakis has given every indication of understanding the need 
to consult with jackson to talk with him and to meet with him 
its a long way to atlanta for dukakis and jackson 
but this political odd couple may be working out their 
differences in ways that could ultimately contribute to a goal both 
share a goal which can now be stated as putting dukakis in the 
white house in january 1989 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
editors note evans witt is a washingtonbased political writer 
for the associated press who has written about every presidential 
campaign since 1976 
