<TEXT>
thousands of chanting demonstrators 
took to the streets of the capital to protest a new law declaring 
islam the state religion of bangladesh 
the demonstrators supporters of opposition political parties 
labor groups and students burned two trucks and stoned seven 
government buses and a police jeep as they marched through dhaka 
tuesday night witnesses said 
several thousand security personnel were posted at key points 
but did not interfere with the demonstrators there were no reports 
of injuries or arrests 
parliament approved the bill by a 254to0 vote tuesday after 15 
opposition lawmakers walked out president hussain muhammad 
ershads jatiya party holds 252 of the assemblys 300 seats and 
two independents joined them in the vote 
nearly 90 percent of bangladeshs 105 million people are 
moslems but the bill had drawn considerable criticism from 
opposition parties womens groups and minority christian hindu 
and buddhist religions 
opposition leader khaleda zia said in a statement after the vote 
tuesday the illegal law bringing about basic change in the 
constitution undermining the independence of the judiciary and 
giving birth to communalism is nothing but a farreaching 
conspiracy to divide the nation 
the present parliament was elected march 3 in elections largely 
boycotted by the nations 48 million voters mrs zia called the 
assembly illegal and said it had no right to transact 
legislative business 
nirmal sen head of the alliance of five parties said the law 
would divide the nation between moslems and nonmoslems 
but syed deedar bakht the jatiya whip in parliament said the 
law would ensure communal harmony and encourage the 
nonmoslems to follow their faiths in total freedom 
i find no reason for the womenfolk to worry about the law as 
under islam both men and women are treated with greater kindness 
in islam than in any other religion he said in an interview 
the bill amends the constitution to insert the sentence the 
religion of the republic is islam but other religions may be 
practiced in peace and harmony 
before the bill was passed prime minister maudud ahmed told 
parliament the measure was needed to free islam from the hands of 
fundamentalists and the traders of religion he tried to assure 
minority groups they need not fear the amendment 
