<TEXT>
the soviet union is discussing working with 
american and other foreign interests to develop vast natural gas 
fields in its arctic siberian and other regions a top soviet 
official says 
joint venture agreements are not signed yet but they are in 
the works soviet gas industry minister victor s chernomyrdin 
told reporters on tuesday at the 17th world gas conference 
he declined to give other details or name the potential foreign 
partners saying premature disclosure could upset the negotiations 
or ruin their business 
earlier tuesday the minister said in a speech to the conference 
that the 1986 disaster at the soviet unions chernobyl nuclear 
power plant has prompted increased use of gas and other fuels to 
make electricity 
chernobyl made it necessary to somewhat limit the production 
of electricity at the nuclear power plants and other kinds of 
power stations have taken on greater loads he said 
chernobyl and other environmental concerns led to huge increases 
in gas production and consumption the past three years in the 
soviet union now the worlds largest natural gas producer the 
minister said from 1984 to 1987 he said soviet gas production 
rose from 5847 billion to 7274 billion cubic meters and 
consumption from 4628 billion to 568 billion cubic meters 
gas exports have increased more than 20fold in the past 15 
years he said dutch gas industry leader ahp grotens told the 
conference western europe nations import 60 billion cubic feet of 
soviet gas annually 
chernomyrdin told reporters that terms of joint ventures are 
still being negotiated but that the soviets will insist on 
retaining majority ownership in any project 
the soviet union seeks foreign collaboration to acquire high 
technology for vast production increases planned for the 21st 
century the minister said 
the soviets face daunting engineering problems in some remote 
and frigid egions he said 
six lengthy pipelines will be needed under the normallyfrozen 
gulf of baidarak for instance to link the huge yamal peninsula on 
the arctic ocean to the rest of the country he said one field on 
the tundra peninsula could yield 200 billion cubic meters of 
natural gas annually by 1990 he said 
