<TEXT>
a private study group says an independent 
oversight agency for the nations 16 major nuclear weapons plants 
should be created because mismanagement has allowed radioactive 
contamination of air soil and water 
the radioactive waste campaign a selfstyled public interest 
group based in new york city made the recommendation in a letter 
to members of congress the letter was released the same day the 
group released a 170page report which charged there are dangerous 
levels of radioactive pollution at all 16 of the energy 
departments main production facilities for nuclear weapons 
the twoyear study by nine researchers concluded there is a 
pattern of gross mismanagement by the department which is allowing 
radioactivity to leak out of the sites through soil water and air 
in many cases intentionally 
many of the problems cited by the report have long been 
acknowledged by the energy department and have been the subjects of 
several blistering reviews by the general accounting office but 
the independent study is the most wideranging report yet published 
on the issue and suggests cleanup costs will exceed the energy 
departments estimate of 100 billion 
the energy department referred calls on the subject to the 
office of an official who was not immediately available for comment 
tuesday 
among key examples of contamination cited by the report 
at the hanford reservation in southeastern washington billions 
of gallons of radioactive water are routinely pumped into the 
ground each year an underground plume of radioactivity stretches 
six miles to the columbia river one of the worlds premier salmon 
runs and an irrigation source for two states 
at the savannah river plant in south carolina millions of 
gallons of radioactive fluids are poured into seepage basins 
actually designed to leak at a steady rate strontium90 which can 
cause bone cancer and leukemia is entering surface water at rates 
43000 times above the governments standard for drinking water 
the report charges further that atlantas water supply is 
threatened by toxic chemicals from the site 
at the feed material production center in fernald ohio 
uranium is contaminating suburban cincinnatis water supply 
at the nevada test site underground nuclear explosions are 
contaminating underground water supplies and radioactive fallout 
has drifted as far as salt lake city 
plutonium one of the most carcinogenic materials known has 
been dispersed into the air or water at weapons facilities near 
dayton ohio santa fe nm and denver 
at oak ridge tenn where three plants are based 35 million 
pounds of uranium are sitting in the ground so theres uranium in 
the runoff in streams and a large amount of uranium put into the 
air resnikoff said thats the largest store of uranium anywhere 
in the country he said 
the group in its letter to congress also called for an 
immediate halt to dumping of radioactive wastes into the ground 
and urged the weapons sites be given top priority for cleanup it 
also called for creation of an independent oversight agency for the 
weapons plants 
the 16 sites covered by the study are 
savannah river plant near aiken sc 
three facilities at oak ridge tenn the y12 plant oak ridge 
national laboratory oak ridge gaseous diffusion plant 
portsmouth gaseous diffusion plant in portsmouth ohio 
feed materials production center in fernald ohio 
mound laboratories in miamisburg ohio 
paducah ky gaseous diffusion plant 
pantex plant amarillo texas 
los alamos national laboratory los alamos nm 
sandia national laboratory albuquerque nm 
rocky flats plant outside denver 
nevada test site about 100 miles from las vegas nev 
lawrence livermore national laboratory livermore calif 
idaho national engineering laboratory idaho falls idaho 
hanford reservation in hanford wash 
marvin resnikoff a nuclear physicist said the nine who 
performed the study reviewed several hundred energy department 
documents and visited some of the sites 
the radioactive waste campaign issues a quarterly newspaper that 
is sent to 13000 members it has five fulltime staff members and 
some parttime workers resnikoff said 
</TEXT>
