federal officials have cited the pacific 
engineering plant in henderson for 123 health and safety violations 
since 1974 the las vegas reviewjournal reported wednesday 
the federal occupational safety and health administration 
released the records after the newspaper requested them under the 
federal freedom of information act 
connie richardson a spokeswoman for the company said pacific 
engineering would not comment 
the plant was destroyed may 4 in a series of blasts that killed 
two people injured 326 and caused 73 million in property damage 
a december 1975 inspection turned up 20 violations including 
use of an inappropriate truck in an area containing combustible 
dust a june 1983 inspection turned up 38 violations including 
failing to have water or a shower near anhydrous ammonia systems 
a may 1983 inspection resulted in 30 violations the biggest of 
which was failing to mark the rated load of a crane 
at least two inspections resulted from accidents at the plant 
state officials have said the number of citations is 
moderate for a company of the size and activity of pacific 
engineering 
meanwhile clark county commissioners have endorsed a proposal 
calling for changes in zoning regulations to provide the county 
better control over hazardous materials one target would be an 
industrial complex at henderson 
the complex includes kerrmcgee chemical corp which 
manufactures the same rocket fuel oxidizer produced nearby at 
pacific engineering the two were the only plants in the country 
that produced the critical rocket fuel oxidizer used in the space 
shuttle and military rockets 
federal officials have announced plans to pay the companies a 
surcharge on the oxidizer to allow kerrmcgee to expand and pacific 
engineering to rebuild 
kerrmcgee halted production on the ammonium perchlorate may 12 
pending safety studies no startup date has been announced 
