the defense department stripped a record 284 
contractors of their right to bid for military work because of 
wrongdoing during the first half of fiscal 1988 according to a 
pentagon report released wednesday 
in addition the bidding rights of another 173 contractors were 
suspended temporarily and 2373 civilian and military indictments 
were obtained alleging contracting improprieties 
the new figures are contained in a semiannual report to 
congress by the pentagons inspector general previously the 
record for debarring defense contractors of bidding rights during a 
sixmonth period was the 275 reported for the last half of fiscal 
1987 
during all of fiscal 1987 the defense department debarred 505 
individuals and companies of their right to bid on contracts an 
annual record 
the latest report which covers the period from oct 1 1987 to 
march 31 also found that pentagon and us army corps of engineers 
auditors saved the government an estimated 31 billion during the 
sixmonth period by challenging questionable awards or future 
contracting plans 
to produce those savings the auditors issued more than 26000 
reports and questioned more than 576 billion in contract costs 
the report said 
another 27 billion was reported saved during the period 
through followup audits aimed at completing cases that originally 
led to management disputes over the auditors recommendations 
among some of the more significant investigative actions cited 
during the period were the racketeering and bribery convictions of 
defense employees at the clothing directorate of a philadelphia 
procurement center a costmischarging case settled by motorola 
inc for 99 million a defective pricing and illegal gratuities 
case against the eaton corp that produced 95 million in 
restitution and a huge defective pricing case settled with bell 
helicopter textron inc for more than 85 million 
the inspector general by law maintains a staff of auditors and 
investigators who operate independently outside the control of top 
pentagon executives the latest report is dated may 30 but was not 
released until wednesday 
in a foreword to the report inspector general june gibbs brown 
wrote the figures demonstrated our commitment to vigorous 
innovative efforts to achieve the widest possible cooperation in 
fighting the misuse of dollars appropriated for the defense of our 
country 
on the investigative side the inspector general said there were 
294 indictments during the period obtained by the justice 
department on the pentagons behalf plus another 143 indictments 
at the local state or foreign level and 1936 recommendations for 
courtsmartial 
