the reagan administration on wednesday 
proposed changing the way the government spends some 750 million a 
year on training hardcore disadvantaged youths for jobs 
labor secretary ann mclaughlin said the administration plans to 
send a bill to congress in the next two weeks that would allow 
local communities to expand the current summeronly program to a 
yearround effort 
it also would change the formula used for allocating the funds 
in order to shift more of them to inner cities where youth 
unemployment is highest particularly among black teenagers 
the current formula established by congress is based on local 
unemployment rates generally the new formula would be based on 
census bureau data on the percentage of disadvantaged youths in a 
communitys population 
we have been concerned for some time on how to reach the most 
disadvantaged youths mrs mclaughlin told the employment 
subcommittee of the senate labor committee cyclical changes in 
unemployment rates may cause large funding swings under the current 
formula that are unrelated to the youth poverty situation in a 
local area 
the program under title iib of the job training partnership act 
now provides about 900 each for sixweek jobtraining programs in 
the summer for about 800000 youths ages 14 to 21 each year 
robert jones assistant labor secretary for job training said 
the changes would allow communities to spend up to 2000 or 3000 
on each youth in the program 
technically we would serve a few less he said but we 
would serve them much more effectively you cant address the youth 
unemployment issue just in terms of numbers you have to do it 
qualitatively 
