<TEXT>
throwing american military might into the 
fight against drug smugglers wont work because suppliers will find 
a way to meet the growing demand in the united states the head of 
the congressional general accounting office said wednesday 
as long as the demand stays high sealing the borders probably 
isnt realistic comptroller general charles bowsher told the 
senate armed services committee 
asked if adding us military forces to the overworked civilian 
law enforcement agencies will help cut drug smuggling bowsher 
replied i dont think we have any statistics that show thats 
going to happen 
military assets are only a marginal assist to the antidrug 
efforts he said 
bowsher noted that even though the amounts of drugs seized have 
increased so have the amounts which slipped through the net 
because drug traffickers have the ability to increase production 
sharply 
bowsher made clear he wasnt suggesting abandoning efforts to 
interdict drugs but he told the panel that an increasing number 
of drug experts believe that the root cause of our national drug 
problem is the demand for illegal drugs 
since our current approach is not working it is time to 
consider devoting more emphasis and more resources aimed at 
reducing demand prevention treatment and research on the causes 
and extent of drug abuse he said 
bowshers assessment was offered as the committee opened a 
series of hearings into proposals to have the pentagon become more 
deeply involved in the antidrug effort 
the house last month voted to order president reagan to have the 
armed forces essentially seal us borders against smugglers the 
senate approved a lessexpanded military role but did decide to 
give navy officers arrest powers for drug boats seized in 
international waters 
the two proposals were added to each chambers defense budget 
bill for the fiscal year starting oct 1 differences between the 
measures including the antidrug provisions will be worked out by 
a housesenate conference committee 
military officials have opposed a wider pentagon role in the 
drug war saying the armed forces lack the necessary training and 
equipment 
sen sam nunn dga the armed services committee chairman 
said it was time to set aside rhetoric and passion and make 
significant improvement in the war on drugs 
sen john warner rva top republican on the panel said 
congress is on a stampede and we need some direction we need 
to try and corral this stampede and point it in the right 
direction 
bowsher said federal officials estimate hey are seizing only 20 
to 25 percent of the cocaine and 10 percent of the marijuana being 
illegally imported into the united states 
if the pentagon does get involved drug traffickers will likely 
react by trying other ways to get the drugs into the united states 
bowsher said 
whenever interdiction has been effectivein the past they 
have been able to move to other ways of importing the drugs he 
said 
he said increasing military support would probably result in 
more drug seizures and arrests and but it may not significantly 
reduce drug supplies because traffickers have shown the ability 
to increase the overall amount involved 
but the military impact could be large he noted pentagon 
officials believe a substantial increase in military assistance 
could adversely affect military readiness 
in addition he noted increasing the military role would be a 
significant departure form this countrys longstanding tradition of 
separating national defense and civilian law enforcement 
responsibilities 
that separations chief legal expression is the posse comitatus 
act an 1878 law that bars using the military to enforce civilian 
laws 
it was amended seven years ago to permit the military to help in 
the antidrug effort but that aid has chiefly been limited to a 
supporting role the militarys major effort has been spotting and 
tracking suspected drug boats or planes 
the federal government is now spending three times more money on 
reducing the supply of drugs than on reducing demand according to 
a gao study 
but the watchdog agency concluded that despite the increased 
funding there is a continuing heavy demand for drugs by us 
consumers americans want drugs and they are willing to pay a high 
price to get them 
bowshers assessment was seconded by a rand corp study that 
said an increased role for the military isnt likely to do much 
good 
</TEXT>
