<TEXT>
the nations largest presbyterian denomination 
prepared wednesday to consider a proposed policy statement 
condemning even the slightest government involvement in church 
affairs 
the policy entitled god alone is lord of the conscience 
would have the 3millionmember presbyterian church usa oppose 
government denials of taxexempt status from religious institutions 
that violate federal laws and attempts to deprogram members of 
cults 
it also would oppose prayer in public schools and the use of 
substantial public funds by religious schools and would defend the 
right of clergy and laity to take part in public affairs including 
running for public office 
the church opened the first full day of its annual meeting 
wednesday by electing rev dr c kenneth hall 63 as moderator 
or chief spokesman for the denomination 
hall pastor of the 640member hill united presbyterian church 
in butler pa defeated four other candidates on the first ballot 
of the 630 delegates 
he said the unusual firstballot win reflected delegates 
concern over the loss of 300000 members since 1983 when the 
denomination was formed by merging the former united presbyterian 
church in the united states of america and the presbyterian church 
in the united states the southern stream 
hall said his victory gave him a mandate to concentrate on 
evangelism and healing in the church he selected 50yearold ruth 
montoya of arvada colo as vice moderator 
the proposed policy paper says government intrudes on religious 
freedom by denying tax exemptions designating churches as 
landmarks and using zoning laws to prohibit church programs 
it calls for the church to continue attention to court cases 
concerning religious liberty and efforts to assure competent legal 
advice on these issues 
the paper prepared by the churchs advisory council on church 
and society was given to the committee on justice and social 
issues for review the full assembly is to vote on the paper 
tuesday the secondlast day of the meeting 
the paper criticizes the us supreme court decision revoking 
the tax exempt status of bob jones university a fundamentalist 
school in south carolina because the independent school did not 
follow federal equal opportunity guidelines 
the paper also criticizes state laws sanctioning forced 
deprogramming of cult members saying the charge of 
brainwashing is exaggerated and the response of deprogramming under 
physical restraint is indefensible 
the paper adds that it is undoubtedly true that television 
evangelists manipulate more peoples emotions in our society than 
do proselytizing cults the paper opposes a constitutional 
amendment to permit public schools to sponsor prayer and the 
use of substantial public funds to support private educational 
systems including tax deductions or credits and use of educational 
vouchers 
presbyterian clergy and laity have a right and responsibility to 
be involved in public affairs including holding elective office 
the paper says 
it also reaffirms the churchs opposition to the appointment of 
a us ambassador to the vatican 
the paper expresses concern about government refusal to 
recognize conduct motivated by conscience such as 
conscientious objection to military service civil disobedience and 
the housing of illegal aliens 
we need not agree with the specific dictates of anothers 
conscience to respect and support the right to exercise that 
conscience the paper says we are called to obey god rather 
than men 
