<TEXT>
the nations highest court on wednesday ruled that 
an american archbishop and two other vatican bank officials cannot 
be prosecuted on fraud charges stemming from the collapse of 
italys biggest private bank 
the constitutional court upheld a lower court ruling that threw 
out arrest warrants against archbishop paul marcinkus president of 
the vatican bank and two other vatican bank officials 
prosecutors accused marcinkus and the two lay officials 
pellegrino de strobel and luigi mennini of being accessories to 
the fraudulent bankruptcy of banco ambrosiano 
the milanbased banco ambrosiano then italys biggest bank 
collapsed in 1982 after it was unable to collect 13 billion in 
loans made to 10 dummy companies in latin america that were 
controlled by the vatican bank 
marcinkus of cicero ill at the time headed the institute for 
religious works the vatican banks formal title 
milan authorities issued arrest warrants in february 1987 for 
marcinkus de strobel and mennini 
the constitutional court on wednesday upheld a previous ruling 
from the court of cassation the lower court threw out the arrest 
warrants because of a vaticanitaly treaty that says the vatican a 
sovereign state is not subject to interference from any italian 
authority 
the constitutional court did not address directly the 
jurisidiction issues raised by the treaty saying only that the 
cassation court had final say in the case 
the court of cassation had rejected a lower court ruling that 
the arrest warrants were legitimate because the bank failure 
occurred in italy 
the vatican bank a major shareholder of banco ambrosiano 
agreed in 1984 to pay 250 million as part of banco ambrosianos 
bankruptcy settlement but it said the payment was not an admission 
of responsibility 
