mother elaine kitowski of manitowish wis attended the hearing 
they declined comment but issued a statement 
we hope the information brought forth in this hearing will 
bring about changes in the naval system to prevent this from ever 
happening again it said in part 
testimony indicated mirecki became frightened during a drill 
left the pool and held on to an equipment rack before a group of 
instructors pried him loose and forced him back into the water 
he then was taken back to the deep end in a headhold by combe 
according to testimony there was conflicting evidence whether 
mirecki collapsed while in combes hold or broke free and put combe 
in a rescue hold successfully completing the drill before he 
collapsed 
prosecutor wynne derided the latter version as a bmovie 
scenario concocted by the defense 
it is unlikely anybody being frightened to death would have 
the calm sense of the moment to perform a maneuver he had been 
unable to do since the beginning of the drill wynne argued 
the defense contended that physical contact was part of the 
rigorous course and that it was not unusual for frightened scared 
or malingering students to be physically forced back into the pool 
