<TEXT>
pan am corps board of directors has authorized 
the ailing airlines management to sell most of pan ams assets if 
agreements on labor concessions are not reached with its unions 
the company also said it would reduce its flight operations more 
than normal after the peak summer travel season 
financial analysts and union leaders characterized the move as 
negotiating pressure but said they also took the threat seriously 
in many respects its a warning shot to the unions said 
john pincavage an airline analyst at the securities firm 
painewebber inc 
the boards decision also could be a sort of trial balloon to 
see what sort of offers emerge for pan ams assets he suggested 
in a letter sent tuesday night to pan am employees chairman 
thomas g plaskett said management was frustrated at not being able 
to get concessions from three of the companys five major unions 
unions representing pilots and flight engineers agreed in 
january to wage cuts and work rule changes that are to save pan am 
240 million over three years but analysts have estimated the 
airline needs to save around 540 million in that period to ensure 
its financial recovery 
the flight attendants teamsters and transport workers unions 
have fought taking pay cuts 
the boards decision authorizes the sale of any of the assets of 
pan american world airways the companys flagship carrier 
without limitation including route segments and divisions 
maintenance and terminal facilities aircraft engines and other 
equipment plasketts letter said 
the only pan am assets which could not be sold are its lucrative 
northeast shuttle service and pan am world services which provides 
ground services to other carriers in airports around the world 
plaskett told employees that as a first step in its new plan 
pan am will substantially reduce the level of its flight 
operations in the fourth quarter far beyond the normal seasonal 
reduction following the summer peak 
pan am also will close its flight service base in san francisco 
on oct 1 and will return two 747 aircraft to their lessors when 
their leases expire at the end of the summer he said 
if agreement is reached with the dissenting unions representing 
flight attendants teamsters and transport workers the assets 
might not be sold pan am spokeswoman pamela hanlon said wednesday 
we can continue along the path of an orderly sale of assets or 
we can find ourselves with a labor agreement soon she said 
there is a very good possibility that the plan to sell assets of 
the company would not go forward 
the company has no specific timetable for selling the assets 
she said 
im taking the letter at face value i presume that theyre 
serious about selling assets said margaret brennan head of the 
flight attendants union at pan am who also heads the joint labor 
council representing the five big unions there 
brennan said the authorization to sell assets could be a tactic 
to pressure recalcitrant unions she cautioned however that i 
dont think theyre going to accomplish anything with the flight 
attendants like this 
pan ams plan to sell assets is a negotiating tactic because 
theyre just fed up with the unions said julius maldutis who 
follows the industry for the investment firm salomon brothers inc 
there are some great risks associated with this strategy but 
pan am had no choice 
among those risks he said are that potential passengers could 
be scared away from pan am flights because of the impending sales 
and that many frequent fliers on the airline could stampede to cash 
in their travel awards 
pan am the nations eighthlargest airline had a net loss of 
833 million in the first quarter the unions representing pilots 
and flight engineers have agreed to concessions totaling about 240 
million over three years but analysts and airline sources believe 
pan am needs around 540 million over the period 
