<TEXT>
the commodity futures trading commission has 
accused refco inc one of the worlds largest trading firms of 11 
commodities law violations 
in addition to chicagobased refco the federal regulatory 
agencys administrative complaint named nine individuals and the 
paragon futures association a defunct company whose trades were 
guaranteed by refco 
woodstock illbased paragon and four individuals settled the 
administrative charges tuesday without admitting wrongdoing the 
charges against refco and five other people will go to a formal 
hearing 
the cftcs complaint alleges that in 1985 the firms and 
individuals made unauthorized trades in customers accounts failed 
to supervise employees and violated recordkeeping and disclosure 
rules 
the most serious charge is churning which means trading a 
customers account often and often unprofitably just to 
generate commissions for brokers 
refco said 12 of paragons customers were affected by the 
alleged churning 
most of the charges involved paragon and its employees the cftc 
said paragon closed shop in july 1985 after customer complaints of 
churning 
refco said it refused to settle the charges with the cftc 
because it should not be punished for the wrongdoing of another 
firm refco also said it terminated paragon after hearing 
complaints of churning 
