means committee and john dingell dmich chairman of the house 
energy and commerce committee headed a drive to block 
consideration of the pepper bill they were irked that the measure 
did not go through their committees 
the bill stirred controversy from the moment the 87yearold 
pepper a wellknown advocate for the elderly said he wanted to 
attach it to another medicare expansion bill the catastrophic 
health initiative scheduled for final passage wednesday in the 
senate 
house leaders feared the weight of peppers plan would sink the 
catastrophic bill which is designed to cushion the financial blow 
of acute illness among the elderly so pepper agreed to withhold 
his measure in exchange for an assurance from house speaker jim 
wright dtexas that there would be a separate floor vote on 
peppers proposal 
as the vote to consider the bill neared republicans and 
democrats alike contended that house rules were being manipulated 
and members were being needlessly forced to vote on a popular but 
unexamined bill five months before an election 
the deliberate legislative process serves us well and 
ultimately saves us all from chaos rostenkowski said in a may 
31 letter to rep jamie whitten dmiss chairman of the house 
appropriations committee appealing for his help in defeating the 
pepper initiative 
i cannot remember a more serious violation of the house 
rules dingell said in a may 23 letter to all members of the 
house furthermore dingell wrote the bill does not pay for 
nursing home costs which are the major sources of financially 
devastating costs for the elderly 
pepper said he didnt include nursing home benefits because he 
wanted to keep the cost of his bill down the sponsor of the 
companion senate bill paul simon dill said 30 percent of 
people in nursing homes would not be there if home services were 
available 
the congressional budget office estimated the pepper program 
would cost 28 billion over five years it would be paid for by 
taxing income above 45000 a year which is now exempt from the 
medicare payroll tax 
cbo said the program would begin running a deficit after the 
fifth year under the bill benefits would be cut and beneficiaries 
charged a copayment to offset any shortfalls 
some house members told pepper they feared passage of his bill 
would undermine chances for developing a more comprehensive 
program including nursing home and home health care next year 
others said the program promised more than it could deliver 
because the agencies and services it required did not yet exist 
the reagan administration opposed the pepper bill and advisers 
to president reagan said they would recommend a veto if it reached 
his desk 
in a recent letter to house minority leader robert michel 
rill health and human services secretary otis r bowen said 
twothirds of the people who would qualify for home care services 
under the pepper bill now receive informal care from family and 
friends 
based on administration calculations bowen predicted the 
program would rack up a 9 billion deficit in 1990 and 26 billion 
by 2000 he said that would put a heavy burden on beneficiaries who 
would have to make up half the deficit through copayments 
among those fighting the pepper bill was the coordinating 
committee for longterm care policy a coalition of insurance and 
business groups that includes the american council of life 
insurance and the us chamber of commerce 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

