<DOCNO> AP880608-0313 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
mexico the worlds sixth largest oil 
producer last month trimmed the average price of its light isthmus 
crude to us clients the government oil monopoly said wednesday 
night 
pemex said in a statement that it charged us customers an 
average of 1578 for a 42gallon barrel in may down from the 16 
of april 
the average price of heavy maya oil rose from 1277 a barrel in 
april to 1307 in may the statement said 
the isthmus and mayaquality crudes that mexico exported 
during the month of may to the american continent had a light 
variation in their quotations with respect to april due to the 
linkage of the prices of mexican oil with the prevailing ones in 
the international market pemex said 
prices for japanese buyers were held steady in may at 1530 a 
barrel for the light oil and 1260 a barrel for the heavy brand 
european customers paid less last month pemex said those 
clients were charged on average 1499 a barrel for isthmus crude 
during the first 15 days of may and 1215 for the maya quality in 
april the average cost for europe was 1543 a barrel for isthmus 
and 1251 for maya 
pemex said mexico exported an average of 1357 million barrels a 
day in may with us buyers taking 51 percent of the total 
spain bought 21 percent of the total and japan was the third 
largest buyer with a 15 percent share 
mexico is not a member of the organization of petroleum 
exporting countries a 13member cartel but it monitors its 
decisions closely and often follows its guidelines on pricing and 
production 
opec members are scheduled to hold their regular midyear 
meeting in vienna austria on saturday they are expected to focus 
their attention on whether to overhaul production quotas 
mexico and five other noncartel nations earlier this year held 
talks with opec about reducing output in an effort to bolster 
sagging world prices 
mexico which has a foreign debt of about 100 billion relies 
on its oil sales to help keep current on its loan payments and buy 
needed imports for its developing economy 
president miguel de la madrid has in recent years pushed to 
reduce the nations dependence on crude exports and build up sales 
of nonoil goods to foreign buyers 
 
</TEXT>
